Actuator Control Interface — REV B (Teensy-Based Servo Control)

OVERVIEW
This document defines the control interface between the main compute system (Raspberry Pi) and the actuator layer using a Teensy microcontroller. The Teensy replaces external servo controllers and is responsible for generating precise, stable PWM signals for all servos.

--------------------------------------------------

SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE

Control Flow:
Raspberry Pi (High-Level Control)
   → Serial Communication (USB or UART)
   → Teensy Microcontroller
   → Direct PWM Output
   → Servo Bank

The Teensy acts as a real-time actuator controller.

--------------------------------------------------

TEENSY ROLE

Primary Responsibilities:
- Generate stable PWM signals for all servos
- Execute motion commands from the Pi
- Enforce safety limits (angle, speed, acceleration)
- Maintain last safe state if communication is lost

Timing Requirements:
- Deterministic signal generation
- No interruption from high-level processing

--------------------------------------------------

SERVO CONTROL SIGNALS

Signal Type:
- PWM (Pulse Width Modulation)

Typical Range:
- 1000µs to 2000µs pulse width

Frequency:
- 50Hz standard (up to 300Hz if supported by servo)

Resolution:
- Minimum 12-bit equivalent precision recommended

--------------------------------------------------

CHANNEL CONFIGURATION

System Example:
- 8 primary servos (hip + knee joints)

Teensy must support:
- Minimum 8 independent PWM outputs
- Prefer hardware timers over software PWM

Pin Assignment:
- Fixed and documented in firmware
- Avoid dynamic reassignment

--------------------------------------------------

COMMUNICATION PROTOCOL

Interface:
- USB Serial (preferred) or UART

Command Structure (Example):
<START><ID><POSITION><SPEED><CHECKSUM><END>

Requirements:
- Compact and deterministic messages
- Error detection (checksum or CRC)
- Acknowledgment for critical commands

Update Rate:
- 50–100 Hz command updates from Pi

--------------------------------------------------

MOTION CONTROL

Handled on Teensy:

- Position interpolation
- Speed limiting
- Acceleration ramping

Critical Rule:
- Do NOT send raw position jumps from Pi
- All movement must be smoothed on the Teensy

--------------------------------------------------

SAFETY FEATURES

Required:

1. Watchdog Timeout
   - If no command received within defined window:
     → Hold position OR move to safe state

2. Motion Limits
   - Per-servo angle constraints
   - Prevent mechanical overextension

3. Rate Limiting
   - Limit max speed and acceleration
   - Prevent current spikes and gear damage

--------------------------------------------------

POWER ISOLATION

- Teensy powered from logic rail (5V regulated)
- Servo power is completely separate (7.4V rail)
- Shared ground is required for signal reference

--------------------------------------------------

FAILURE MODES

Potential Issues:
- Lost communication with Pi
- PWM jitter due to poor timing
- Electrical noise from servo power system

Mitigation:
- Hardware timers for PWM
- Shielded or short signal lines
- Watchdog reset behavior

--------------------------------------------------

FIRMWARE REQUIREMENTS

- Real-time loop for PWM updates
- Non-blocking serial communication
- State machine for command parsing
- Fault detection and handling

Recommended Structure:
- Input handler
- Motion planner
- Output driver

--------------------------------------------------

SYSTEM CONSTRAINTS

- Teensy must never be overloaded with high-level logic
- Keep firmware focused on real-time control only
- All AI, navigation, and planning stay on the Pi

--------------------------------------------------

